[3]
Date: 5 Feb 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com
Source: Frankfurter Rundschau, 5 Feb 2001 [edited]

Majority of Spanish Farmers Infringe BSE Guidelines
---------------------------------------------
MADRID: Spanish police have registered more than 2000 violations of
European Union (EU) regulations introduced to help fight BSE or so-called
mad cow disease in 3000 spot checks. The infringements were so serious in a
dozen cases criminal proceedings were instituted and 7 arrests were made.
More than 1500 members of a special squad of the Guardia Civil started
checking farms, abattoirs, incinerators, transport companies, feed
manufacturers and other meat-processing plants last December [2000]. The
squad, which is responsible to the environmental protection division of the
police, investigated for 6 weeks whether the plants are observing the EU
regulations on tackling the disease.
The results of the initially-limited campaign were so horrifying the
director-general of the Guardia Civil, Santiago Lopez Valdivielso,
immediately extended the investigational order. A time limit on the
controls is no longer planned. Lopez said most of the facilities inspected
had not adhered to the rules and some had become conspicuous as a result of
several infringements of the EU standards.
A spokesman for the environmental protection department pointed out the
number of registered infringements and crimes did not decline but increased
continuously towards the end of the campaign. The spokesman said violations
of both EU rules and standards decreed by the Spanish government were
manifold: farmers even forged the certificates of origin of their cattle.
The officers found tons and tons of animal feed containing bone meal
throughout the country; animal carcasses were not buried in keeping with
regulations; and abattoir waste ended up on rubbish-heaps. In view of this
blatantly deplorable state of affairs, agriculture minister Miguel Arias
Canete and health minister Celia Villalobos have decoded on [proposed?] new
measures against the disease, in agreement with regional governments.
The state now wants to buy up all animal feed containing meat. In order to
halt the collapse of the beef market, the authorities intend to buy large
quantities of cattle. It was also agreed dead cattle would be allowed to be
buried in exceptional cases.
--
