[4]
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters, 7 Feb 2001 [edited]

ROME - At least 100 countries are at risk from mad cow disease (BSE, Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy), the head of the United Nations' (UN) world food
body said on Wednesday. "FAO estimates between 1986-96 up to today,
meat-and-bone meal (MBM) from Europe was exported to more than 100
countries," Jacques Diouf, director-general of the Rome-based UN Food and
Agriculture Organisation (FAO), told Reuters.
"Around 100 countries imported live cattle. Some countries also re-exported
MBM to third countries," Diouf said in a written answer to Reuters'
questions about BSE.
"All countries which have imported cattle or MBM originating from Western
Europe, during and since the 1980s, can therefore be considered at risk
from the disease," Diouf added.
"Regions having imported sizeable quantities of meat meal from the UK
during and since the 1980s include the Near East, Eastern Europe and Asia,"
he said.
He said the least likely risks were in Latin America, Australia and New
Zealand because of the nature of their industries, systems of production
and sources of MBM.
--
