Date: 8 Feb 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com
Source: Straits Times, 8 Feb 2001 [edited]
<http://straitstimes.asia1.com.sg/>

HONGKONG -- Hong Kong denied public hospitals had used British blood
products contaminated with the human form of mad-cow disease. A statement
released by the Hong Kong Hospital Authority confirmed "public hospitals
have neither imported nor used the immunoglobulin concerned."
This announcement follows claims by the Singapore government that 3 vials
of a blood product from donors suffering from Creutzfeld-Jakob Disease
(vCJD) -- a human form of the brain-wasting Bovine Spongiform
Encephalopathy (BCE) or mad-cow disease -- had been delivered to the territory.
The Singapore health ministry said in a statement the Hong Kong-based
Inchcape JHD had received the shipment, not Inchcape in Singapore. Inchcape
is a diversified British-controlled group with operations across Asia.
Bio Products Laboratory (BPL), a branch of Britain's National Health
Service, had earlier confirmed the sale to Singapore based on documentation
procedures linking a blood donor's name to the product made.
Each vial is given a batch number and the country to which it is sent is
recorded.
